<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-01-12T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-01-12T04:00:00-05:00" n="311" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d311">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894c.111/21: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Crane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-01-12T17:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">January 12,
                                        1921—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received January 12—11:08
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>22. Your 10, January 8, 4 p.m. To avoid any possible ambiguity I suggest
                            addressing following note to Japanese Minister: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“I have the honor to state in amplification of my note[s] of
                                    November 2nd and January 5th that the discontinuance after
                                    January 15th of my Government’s acquiescence in the application
                                    to American citizens of certain passport regulations of the
                                    Japanese Government applies equally to the Mukden–Antung railway
                                    and the Shantung railway outside of the leased territory.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>Does Department concur?</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Crane</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>